QUENNE v2.0 – Technical Specification

Quantum Edge Neuromorphic Engine for Intelligent Infrastructure

Version: 2.0
Author: Nicolas E. Santiago
Organization: QUENNE Research Institute
Date: January 2026

⸻

1. System Purpose

QUENNE v2.0 is a distributed cognitive control fabric designed to govern:
   •   AI systems
   •   data centers
   •   energy infrastructure
   •   smart cities
   •   cloud and edge compute

It provides real-time optimization, resilience, and sovereignty across cyber-physical systems.

⸻

2. Architectural Overview

QUENNE is a four-layer closed-loop control system.
Sensors → Neuromorphic Control → Quantum Optimization → Multi-Agent Governance → Actuation → Sensors

This loop runs continuously across cloud, edge, and physical infrastructure.

⸻

3. Core Subsystems

3.1 Telemetry & Sensor Fabric

Collects:
   •   Power (kW, harmonics, UPS, battery SoC)
   •   Thermal (rack temp, airflow, coolant)
   •   Compute (CPU, GPU, memory, network)
   •   Cyber (traffic, anomalies, intrusion)
   •   Environmental (grid price, carbon, weather)

Interfaces:
   •   IPMI, SNMP, Modbus, BACnet, OPC-UA
   •   Kubernetes metrics
   •   Smart grid APIs

⸻

3.2 Neuromorphic Control Layer

Purpose: fast, local stabilization

Functions:
   •   anomaly detection
   •   thermal runaway prevention
   •   power spike damping
   •   fault prediction

Technology:
   •   Spiking neural networks
   •   Event-driven inference
   •   Low-power edge AI

Latency: < 10 ms
Power budget: ultra-low (edge-deployable)

⸻

3.3 Quantum-Inspired Optimization Layer

Purpose: global decision making

Solves:
   •   workload placement
   •   power dispatch
   •   cooling strategies
   •   routing
   •   battery scheduling

Techniques:
   •   Ising models
   •   annealing
   •   stochastic solvers
   •   QAOA-style heuristics

Inputs:
   •   digital twin state
   •   constraints (SLA, power, carbon, security)

Outputs:
   •   optimal actions for schedulers, power systems, cooling

⸻

3.4 Multi-Agent Governance (TRIAD)

Agent
Role
Michael
System governance, priority resolution
Gabriel
Security, resilience, anomaly arbitration
Rafael
Global optimization and long-term planning

Capabilities:
   •   conflict resolution
   •   trust scoring
   •   risk assessment
   •   adaptive policy evolution

⸻

3.5 Actuation Layer

Controls:
   •   Kubernetes / VM schedulers
   •   GPU power caps
   •   cooling systems
   •   UPS & battery systems
   •   network routing
   •   smart grid interfaces

Provides closed-loop execution.

⸻

4. Platform Integration

QUENNE v2.0 provides native support for:
Platform
QUENNE AI
QUENNE LLM
QUENNE AI OS
QUENNE AI Server OS
QUENNE Smart City

It also powers:
   •   external AI
   •   cloud providers
   •   data centers
   •   smart infrastructure

⸻

5. Security Architecture

Includes:
   •   zero-trust control plane
   •   cryptographic telemetry
   •   neuromorphic intrusion detection
   •   multi-agent verification
   •   quantum-resistant planning

Fail-safe:
   •   isolate compromised components
   •   revert to safe operating modes

⸻

